\end{compactenum}
}
\vspace{1.3cm}

\textbf{Systemic effects} are system-wide effects which are triggered through local interaction. 
That means, systemic effects in a system can not be boiled down to a simple aggregate of properties of its units but only to more complex ones. 
The understanding of systemic effects in socio-economic systems is crucial for good anticipation of potential societal change and the proper design of societal institutions. 
Entanglement and understanding of some relations of microscopic action and interaction and macroscopic effects is the core contributions of this habilitation. 

Studying potential systemic effects scientifically requires a well-suited description of the units of a system and their action and interaction. 
For socio-economic systems that means the development of an agent-based model with humans (or organisations or humans) as the agents. 
\textbf{Agent-based models} are studied with computer simulation. 
The work flow and how it is used to tackle political science research questions is the subject of \textcite{Lorenz2012ZurMethodeder} which is part of the habilitation work.
% \begin{center}
%   \begin{minipage}{0.9\textwidth}
%     \begin{flushleft}
%        \fullcite{Lorenz2012ZurMethodeder}
%     \end{flushleft}
%   \end{minipage}
% \end{center}
The basis of simulation is formal modeling, which is to map the real world in a simplifying way to a mathematical framework and ultimately into an algorithm to be implemented for simulation. 

The actions and interactions of agents in the model are defined through behavioral rules which are usually modeled in a simple direct way and not necessarily based on utility maximization. This distinguishes agent-based models from game-theoretic ones which are based on rational choice decision making. 
Agents in typical agent-based models apply these rules repeatedly in response to the changing societal context they observe. 
The idea of rational-choice models is that rational actors anticipate the potential rational moves of others which implies that all immediately switch to rational play such that action form a certain type of game-theoretic equilibrium. In game-theory, the existance and uniqueness of equilibrium solutions is of first interest and not so much, if and how an equilibrium is reached and which if this is not uniqueness. 

Some agent-based modelers therefore emphasize that they are able to study systems dynamics ``out of equilibrium''.  
Although the dynamical perspective is indeed lacking to a large extent in rational choice theories like game theory, the oppositional view of agent-based and rational choice models is mostly overstated.
First, every dynamical model -- also with the simplest behavioral rules -- has the tendency to approach attractive fixed points (equilibria), either static, stochastic, cyclic, or chaotic.  
Second, behavioral rules can often be derived from properly designed utility functions which agents maximize or satisfice. The utility maximizing and the behavioral rules framework are thus not necessary contrary but can be identical. This is further discussed in \textcite{Lorenz2012ZurMethodeder}.

Finally, game theoretic reasoning can also be fed into a dynamical agent-based model through an evolutionary or boundedly rational setting, where actors do rational-choice decision only with respect to information from a smaller subset players and anticipate only with a limited time horizon. In that sense, also rational-choice models give rise to systemic effects which go beyond the scope of the individual. 

\textcite{Groeber.Lorenz.ea2014Dissonanceminimizationas} (another part of the habilitation work) show an example how behavioral rules in models of continuous opinion dynamics can be microfounded as short-sighted (or myopic) best response of an individual to minimize opinion dissonance within its social context. In particular, the paper shows under what conditions of the dissonance function, dissonance minimization can serve as a microfoundation of averaging as the behavioral rule in opinion dynamics models. In that sense, agents in many opinion dynamics models appear as boundedly rational agents which links agent-based modeling back to decision and game theory. 
\smallskip 

In this habilitation work, agent-based modeling is either theory-driven (two works) or partly data-driven (four works).
\textbf{Theory-driven modeling} starts with a plausible setup of variables, parameters and microscopic behavioral rules. 
\textbf{Data-driven modeling} starts with the exploration of observation data by the extraction of interesting non-trivial stylized macroscopic facts. 
Either way, the idea is to explain macroscopic phenomana through human interaction on the microscopic level. 
Models always simplify the real-world therefore in some sense every model is wrong in capturing reality. The art of modeling lies in the selection of relevant aspects in relevant relations such that the phenomena of interest are captured most appropriate by few variables and few parameters. 

Lastly, systemic effects in social systems are also explored through controlled \textbf{group experiments} (four works). 

