\item \fullcite{Lorenz2009Universalityofmovie}
\item \fullcite{Lorenz2015ModelingEvolutionIdeological}
\end{compactenum}
}
\vspace{1.3cm}

When individuals form opinions on certain topics these are based on the one hand on individual knowledge, experience, and emotions, but on the other hand opinions are to a large extent intrinsically social. 
We as citizens, employees, consumers, and in other roles adjust our existing opinions once we hear the opinions of others because we learn new information, because we want to conform with, or confront the opinions of others. Sometimes we consciously might form our opinions entirely based on how it best fits in the opinion landscapes of our social environment (see \textcite{Groeber.Lorenz.ea2014Dissonanceminimizationas}). 

How individuals adjust their opinions with respect to messages from others has been studied in \emph{social psychology} in the field of \emph{attitude research}.
The focus of the \emph{opinion dynamics} goes beyond the individual and studies the effect which the repeated simultaneous opinion formation and opinion adjustments transforms and shapes the entire opinion landscape. Thus, opinion dynamics extends the view from individual processes to systemic processes triggered by them. 

\bigskip


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% CHAPTER 2, TOPIC 1, Tipping Diffusivity %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\paragraph{Tipping diffusivity and why more links can lead to less consensus.} The first habilitation work on opinion dynamics is another theoretical contribution: \textcite{Shin.Lorenz2010TippingDiffusivityin}. 
We model a situation of two equally sized communities of agents which both are characterized by a typical number of intra-community links between agents of the same community and a typically lower number of inter-community links of members from different communities. 
All agents hold an opinion which is a real numbers between -1 and +1. It might represent a tendency towards different opposing cultures, while zero represents no opinion on this. 
Our point of analysis is to further assume that initially all agents of each community hold the same opinion, while 
one community has a negative one, and the other a positive one. 
``Negative'' and ``positive'' are used in the mathematical sense here, abstracting from any value judgment. 
Our theoretical question is under what conditions on the amount and ratio of intra- vs. inter-community links can these communities maintain their different opinions. 

The opinion dynamics is modeled as an information accumulation system \parencite{Shin2009Informationaccumulationsystem}. Information means here opinion towards one of the two opposites -1 or +1. In each iteration agents on the one hand forget part of that information (which would imply convergence to the ground state zero) and accumulate on the other hand opinions of the agents within their network which includes many agents from the same community and few agents from the other community. As we assume that all agents start with the same opinion as the others in their community and all have the same amount of intra- and inter-community links, their opinions will always move synchronously and we can study just two dynamical equations as $y_1$ and $y_2$ for the opinion in each community. 
The global variables of the model are: the intra-community diffusivity $\Omega_0$, the inter-community diffusivity $\Omega_X$, and the rate of forgetting $\Delta$ (diffusivities are uniformly derived from the number of intra- and inter-community links). The dynamical equations and their derivation from the agent-based model are shown in \textcite{Shin.Lorenz2010TippingDiffusivityin}. 

We are able to completely characterize the dynamics of this system, including all fixed points, their status of attractivity and stability, and their basins of attraction. Figure \ref{fig:ShinLorenz} shows a phase diagram with respect to intra- and inter-community diffusivities. It shows which fixed points of which kind exist in which regions of the phase space.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{figs/fig2_3_blog-crop.pdf}
\caption{Phase diagram of intra- vs. inter-community diffusivity $(\Omega_0,\Omega_X)$ parameterized by the rate of forgetting $\Delta$ (top), with five exemplary $(y_1,y_2)$-planes which show the fixed points for the opinions of the two communities and their basins of attraction for different initial opinions (center), and with ten exemplary trajectories over time for different initial opinions (periphery). } \label{fig:ShinLorenz}
\end{figure}

The most interesting prediction of the model is summarized in the title of the paper: ``More links, less consensus''. This result can be best understood by following the red arrow in Figure \ref{fig:ShinLorenz}. This arrow represents situations where there are always four times more intra-community links than inter-community links but along the arrow the total number of links for each agent increases. The phase diagram is parameterized in units of the rate of forgetting. When we follow the arrow diffusivity increases (under constant ratio intra vs. inter) with respect to the rate of forgetting. The ``travel'' goes as follows:
\begin{compactenum}[(1)]
 \item Initially we are in the trivial zone. The rate of forgetting dominates and trajectories converge to the ground state or ``no opinion'' for any initial opinions. 
 \item We cross the border to the consensus zone. Now two fixed points emerge, and both communities converge to a either a positive or a negative opinion. The system converges to the opinion of the community starting with the more extreme opinion. It is still possible for the system to converge to the ground state but only for a thin set of initial values (shown as a white diagonal line). This is a typical example of an unstable but attractive fixed point. 
 \item We cross the dotted line and are still in the consensus zone, but two unstable fixed points with coexisting different opinions in communities emerge. Even the smallest fluctuation in opinions around these fixed points of coexistence would bring the system to the basin of attractio of one of the two consensual fixed points. 
 \item We cross the border to the coexistence zone where both coexistence fixed point become stable. The further we go the larger their basins of attraction grow. 
\end{compactenum}
One reason for the emergence of the coexistence zone that the dynamical equation has a saturation component which prevents that agents accumulate information in one direction ad infinitum. Information saturates at either +1 or -1, which seems like a reasonable assumption.

A hypothesis which one can derive from this model is that coexistence of different cultures in connected communities is more likely when the overall connectivity is larger. We think that this might be part of an explanation for the increasing polarization and fragmentation of political debates which seems to happen nowadays through increasing  connectivity through social networks on the internet. The next step should be to bring this hypothesis to an empirical test. 

