With a procedure documented in the paper, confined $(\alpha,\beta,\gamma,\mu)$-histograms were fitted to the empirical IMDb-histograms. Figure \ref{fig:LevyParams} shows how the fitted $\alpha$, $\beta$ and $\gamma$ are distributed with respect to $\mu$. The figure shows that the smallest scale parameter $\gamma$ as well as no skewness ($\beta=0$) appear both for $\mu\approx 7.5$ which coincides with the overall average $\mu$. Further on, the peakedness $\alpha$
is relatively constant at around $\frac{4}{3}$ with respect to $\mu$. Skewness shows a linear trend with movies better than average being left-skew and movies worse than average being right skew. That means, better movies even have a fatter tail in the very good ratings, while bad movies have a fatter tail in the bad ratings. The scale parameter increases in a parabolic form when deviting from the average rating. That mean non-average movies show more dispresion. Form these regularities -- linear $\beta$, quadratic $\gamma$, and constant $\alpha$ -- a one-parameter fit called {$\mu$-fit} was constructed and all movies where fitted again by only using the parameter $\mu$. The other three parameters of the confined $(\alpha,\beta,\gamma,\mu)$-histograms are just functions of $\mu$ corresponding to the green lines in Figure \ref{fig:LevyParams}.

