\vspace{1.3cm}

Growth is fundamental to all living organisms. 
 Societal growth is the growth of a societal value such as total wealth or total productivity in a society composed of individuals which act mostly independent but also interrelated through interaction or societal institutions. 
 Macroeconomic growth can be defined analogously. % TODO Check 
 Whether a society or economy experiences growth or decline, can critically depend on this coupling of individual growth process. 
 The three   two contributions to systemic effects on societal growth. 

 First, \textcite{Koenig.Lorenz.ea2016Innovationvsimitation} show how innovation together with imitation of technology optimizes productivity growth in an economy of independent firms. 
 The second contribution \parencite{Lorenz.Paetzel.ea2013Redistributionspursgrowth}, shows how redistribution of wealth through proportional taxation and redistribution as equal lump-sums can spur growth. 
 
 
 Such growth through redistribution is triggered when individual growth is proportional but rates of growth (or decline when below one) are partly stochastic. 
 The latter results poses the question if and how a democratic society is capable of realizing the desired levels of redistribution. 
 An experimental study \parencite{Lorenz.Paetzel.ea2016JustDontCall} on framing of collective decisions about redistribution shows an important aspect of the answer to this question There is a higher propensity to high tax rates  
\bigskip

\paragraph{How innovation and imitation drive growth of productivity.} \textcite{Koenig.Lorenz.ea2016Innovationvsimitation} show how innovation together with imitation of technology maximized productivity growth in an economy of firms. The theory reproduces the empirical fact that the productivity distribution of domestic firms in existing economies are travelling waves with left and right tails following power laws. 

